prompt: Can you share a specific experience where you had to collaborate with a diverse group of individuals who had differing opinions or work styles? How did you navigate those differences to achieve a common goal, and what was the outcome of that collaboration?
main_response:
Yeah, this actually reminds me of a group project I did for my Human-Centered Design class. Our team had four people, and we were all pretty different in how we approached work. One person was super design-focused—like really passionate about UI/UX details—and another was all about functionality and fast iteration. I was somewhere in the middle, trying to balance both. The main conflict started when we were deciding how polished our prototype needed to be for the final presentation. The design person wanted to spend a bunch of time refining the visuals, but the other person felt like that was a waste and kept pushing to just focus on getting it working. Meetings got kind of tense, and people were talking over each other or tuning out completely.
I tried to step in more as a moderator, even though I wasn’t officially the team lead. I set up a shared doc where we listed out the requirements and broke them into “must-haves” and “nice-to-haves,” so we could align on priorities. I also suggested we set timeboxes—like, give the designer a few hours to polish the homepage, and then pivot to finishing the backend logic. That way, everyone felt heard and we stayed on schedule.In the end, we finished a prototype that looked clean and actually worked. The presentation went well, and I think what I learned was that you don’t need everyone to work the same way—you just need to find a structure that respects their strengths while keeping things grounded in the end goal. It also made me realize how helpful it is to put things in writing when there’s disagreement. Having shared notes and task lists helped us stay aligned even when we didn’t agree on everything.
followup_response:
Yeah, there was a meeting about a week before our final presentation where things got really tense—the designer wanted to redo the onboarding flow because it didn’t feel smooth enough, but the backend teammate was visibly annoyed and said something like, “Why are we spending time on stuff that doesn’t matter if it doesn’t even work?” and it felt like the whole conversation was about to spiral, so I stepped in and shared my screen with our shared doc and said, “Let’s just break this down—what’s the bare minimum version that we can commit to by tomorrow night?” and once we listed that out, I said, “If we hit that, then we can use any leftover time to polish,” and they both actually agreed right away, which kind of surprised me but also showed that having a neutral process to focus on helped shift the energy, and from that I realized that a lot of conflict isn’t about people being difficult—it’s about not having a shared framework for moving forward, so now when I sense that
tension I try to immediately ground it in priorities and timelines everyone can see.
summary: In a Human-Centered Design group project, I mediated conflicts between team members with differing priorities on design and functionality by creating a shared document to outline project requirements and implementing timeboxes for tasks. This approach facilitated collaboration, allowing us to deliver a polished and functional prototype for our final presentation, while also teaching me the importance of structure and written communication in resolving disagreements.

prompt: Can you describe a time when you set a personal or professional goal that you ultimately did not achieve? What specific steps did you take to try to reach that goal, what obstacles did you encounter, and how did you handle the situation once you realized you weren't going to succeed?
main_response:
Yeah, I set a goal last summer to finish building this personal finance app I started during the school year—I wanted to launch a beta version by the end of August and maybe even let friends try it, so I created a roadmap in Notion, broke it into weekly milestones, and committed to coding at least an hour a day, but once my internship started I totally underestimated how mentally drained I’d be after work, and on top of that I was also taking an online algorithms course and trying to stay active socially, so I kept pushing the project off thinking I’d catch up later, and by mid-August I realized there was no way I’d finish it on time, which honestly felt like a letdown because I had talked about it a lot and felt like I was falling behind my own expectations—but I ended up reframing it by doing a short reflection doc where I wrote out what went wrong, and I realized the issue wasn’t motivation, it was overcommitting without clear fallback plans, so since then I’ve tried to set softer deadlines
for side projects and prioritize based on energy, not just ambition.
followup_response: Yeah, so in the reflection doc I made a simple three-part structure: first I listed what I originally planned and why I thought it mattered, then I wrote out all the things that got in the way—like specific dates where I skipped progress, why I skipped, and what I was doing instead—and finally I asked myself what I could’ve changed without burning out, and from that I realized I needed to plan around energy levels not just time blocks, so for my next project—a Discord bot I built for my study group—I set super low-pressure goals like “code one small feature per weekend,” and I gave myself two full months instead of a few weeks, and that slower pace actually helped me stay consistent and finish it without feeling overwhelmed.
summary: Failed to launch personal finance app by August due to overcommitment; learned to set softer deadlines and prioritize energy.

prompt: Can you describe a time when you were part of a team that faced a significant challenge or setback? What role did you play in addressing the issue, how did you support your teammates during this difficult time, and what did you learn from the experience that you apply in team settings today?
main_response:
Yeah, one time that stands out was during a group project in my software engineering class where we were building a budgeting web app, and about a week before the deadline one of our teammates told us they had to drop the class for personal reasons, which was a huge blow because they were handling the main dashboard feature and we hadn’t touched it yet, so the rest of us had to suddenly redistribute a big chunk of work under time pressure—my role was backend, but I volunteered to pick up the dashboard since I had some experience with React, and I also helped the others reorganize our Trello board and set daily check-ins just to keep everyone on the same page and not fall apart, and even though we were stressed, I kept reminding the team that if we focused on one task at a time, we could still turn in something solid,
which we did—the final product wasn’t as polished as we’d originally planned but it worked and got good feedback, and I think what I learned from that was how important it is to stay solution-focused when plans fall apart, and that small things like organizing check-ins or keeping people calm can have a huge impact on a team’s ability to recover.
followup_response:
Yeah, one specific challenge was figuring out how to sync the dashboard’s expense graphs with the backend data in real-time because the original teammate had planned to use a different charting library than what I was familiar with, so I had to learn Chart.js from scratch in like two days while also wiring up the API calls correctly, and at first the graphs weren’t updating properly when users added new entries—it turned out I was missing a state update in React that prevented re-rendering, so after a few hours of debugging I fixed it by lifting the state up and using a custom hook to refetch the data on every form submission, and when I showed the working version in our next team call, people were super relieved and one of my teammates messaged me afterward saying, “Honestly dude, you kept us on track when it felt like we were gonna crash,” which meant a lot, and that whole experience taught me that even if you’re not the most experienced person on the team, just stepping in and keeping things
moving can make a big difference.
summary: Faced with a teammate's departure, I led the team in redistributing tasks, ensuring project completion and positive feedback despite challenges.

prompt: Can you share an experience from your life—whether in a team project, a volunteer role, or a personal endeavor—where you took on a leadership position but faced a significant failure? What actions did you take to lead and support your team, what went wrong, and how did you respond to the outcome?
main_response:
Yeah, so I led a team for a student hackathon where our goal was to build a study tracker app that gamified productivity with a point system, and I took charge of organizing the timeline, assigning roles, and setting up our GitHub repo and task board, but I underestimated how much work the integration between the frontend and backend would take and didn’t leave enough time for testing, so even though each part worked separately, we hit a wall the night before the demo when we realized the app kept crashing on login due to an auth bug I hadn’t accounted for, and we all stayed up trying to fix it but ran out of time and had to present a demo video of disconnected features instead of a live walkthrough, which felt like a huge letdown, but after the event I sent a reflection doc to the team outlining what I learned and took full responsibility, and we did a short debrief where people shared feedback and appreciated that I owned up to the planning gaps—what I took from that was that being a leader doesn’t
mean getting everything right, it means owning the outcome and making space for the team to learn and move forward even when things flop.
followup_response:
Yeah, after the hackathon I messaged everyone and asked if they’d be open to a short debrief call—not to dwell on the failure but just to talk about what went well and what we’d do differently next time—so I started the call by taking ownership of the poor time allocation and said something like, “I know the integration issues were on me for not budgeting time properly, and I really appreciate how hard you all worked despite that,” and then I asked each person to share one thing they thought worked well and one thing they’d change if we did another project together, and I kept notes in a shared doc so everyone could see it, and what stuck with me most was that a few teammates said they felt like they didn’t fully understand the overall plan or timeline and wished I’d checked in more often, which helped me realize that even if I feel organized in my head, I need to over-communicate when I’m leading, so now in group projects I make sure to write out detailed timelines and do quick daily syn
s to avoid that same confusion.
summary: Led a team in a hackathon; faced integration issues, presented a video instead, and learned the importance of accountability.

prompt: Can you describe a time when you faced a situation where your personal values were challenged, either in a work, school, or community setting? How did you navigate that situation, and what steps did you take to ensure that your actions aligned with your principles, even if it was difficult or unpopular?
main_response:
Yeah, this reminds me of my first year in college when I was taking a data structures class and got overwhelmed during a week full of midterms—one of my friends sent me a GitHub repo with a full solution to the assignment we were working on, and I was really tempted to just copy a piece of it because I was stuck on the collision handling part of a hash map and honestly didn’t think I had time to figure it out on my own, but after hovering over the code for a bit I stopped and thought about how I’d feel if someone asked me to explain it in an interview or how I’d feel if I actually got caught, and it just didn’t sit right with me, so I closed the tab, made some tea, and decided to write out everything I didn’t understand and use that to go back through the lecture slides and documentation, and even though I turned it in a bit late and lost a few points, I ended up learning way more and felt way better knowing it was my own work—since then I’ve been a lot more intentional about sticking to my
values, even when the easy option looks tempting in the moment.
summary: Faced with academic pressure, I chose integrity over shortcuts, leading to deeper understanding and commitment to my values.

prompt: Can you share an experience from your life where you witnessed a colleague, teammate, or friend engaging in unethical behavior, and you felt compelled to intervene? What actions did you take, what challenges did you face in doing so, and what was the outcome of that situation?
main_response:
Yeah, during a group project in one of my CS classes, a teammate admitted in a private message that they’d copied part of their code from an online source without citing it, and they asked me not to say anything because “everyone does it,” but it didn’t feel right to just ignore it since we were submitting as a team and our names were all on the final report, so I told them directly that I wasn’t comfortable turning it in unless they either rewrote the section or disclosed it properly, and they were kind of annoyed at first and said I was overreacting, but after a day they came back and agreed to redo the function from scratch and asked me to help them understand the logic, so we worked on it together and ended up submitting something that was actually cleaner and more in line with the assignment goals—honestly it was awkward, and I was worried I’d make things worse in the moment, but it made me realize that saying something doesn’t have to be confrontational if you keep the focus on doing
the right thing for the group.
followup_response: Yeah, when I messaged them I started by keeping the tone really neutral—I said something like, “Hey, I saw what you mentioned about copying that code and I totally get that this class is stressful, but since it’s a group submission I just want to be honest that I’m not comfortable turning it in unless it’s original or cited,” and I made sure to avoid accusing them or making it personal, and instead framed it as a team issue that could affect all of us, and I also said I was happy to help walk through the logic with them if they wanted to redo it, which I think helped lower the defensiveness because I wasn’t just pointing fingers—I was offering support too, and that experience really shaped how I see integrity in teams now, like it’s not just about doing your own part right, it’s also about making sure your team is moving in the right direction together, even if it means having uncomfortable conversations.
summary: Confronted a teammate about plagiarism; they rewrote the code, improving the project and fostering collaboration while upholding integrity.

prompt: Can you describe a time when you had multiple important commitments or deadlines overlapping, such as work projects, school assignments, or personal obligations? How did you prioritize your tasks, manage your time effectively, and ensure that you met all your responsibilities? Please walk us through your thought process and the strategies you used to stay on track.
main_response:
Yeah, during midterms last semester I had a CS project due, a stats exam the next day, and a club workshop I had committed to lead all in the same 3-day window, and at first I kind of panicked and thought I’d have to drop something, but I took a step back and made a time-blocked schedule in Google Calendar where I broke everything into small chunks, like “study probability for 90 minutes” or “debug login feature for 2 hours,” and I also built in short breaks so I wouldn’t burn out, then I ranked everything by urgency and weight—so I finished the CS project first because it was due earliest and worth 25% of my grade, then shifted focus to the stats review, and for the club workshop I reached out to a friend and asked if they could co-lead it with me so I could cut prep time in half, and by spreading it all out and not trying to multitask everything at once, I ended up hitting all the deadlines without pulling an all-nighter, and it made me realize that even when things pile up, clarity and
structure usually beats panic.
followup_response: Yeah, one challenge was that even though I had everything blocked out, some tasks took longer than I expected—like debugging the CS project ended up being more complicated because of a bug with async state updates, so it ate into my stats study time, and I started to feel behind even though I technically had a plan, so what I did was shift some of the less urgent study blocks to later in the evening and cut one of my breaks shorter, and I also decided to skip watching lecture videos at 1.5x speed and just reviewed slides and practice problems instead to save time, and what I learned is that time-blocking works best when you treat it as a flexible framework, not a rigid schedule—like it gave me structure, but I had to adjust it on the fly when things changed, and that helped me stay calm instead of throwing the whole plan out when one part ran long.
summary: Faced with multiple deadlines, I created a schedule, prioritized tasks, and collaborated, successfully meeting all deadlines without stress.

Challenge: haha yeah we were just like 😳 “oops” lol. we dumped it and started over 😅 and we were way more careful the second time. like counting every drop out loud lmao. it actually turned out fine after that but we were lowkey so nervous the whole time 🧪💦
umm yeah so like… we made sure to go way slower with the burette? and we were watching the color super closely that time 😅 i held the flask and she did the drops, and we kept checking with each other like “is it pink yet??” lol. and we also had the TA double check before we stopped just to be safe 🙈
Actions: hmm i guess like… double checking stuff with your partner is really helpful?? and also not rushing even if you feel kinda behind 😅 we were trying to go fast the first time and that’s why we messed up lol. so yeah i think just like… slowing down and actually talking through each step made a big difference 🧪🫶
umm yeah there was this part where the color just started to change and i was like “wait i think it’s turning??” and she stopped right away and was like “okay let’s go drop by drop now” 😅 and that helped a lot cuz we weren’t just like doing our own thing, y’know? it felt more like we were actually working together instead of just hoping it turns out right lol
Results: yeahh we actually got a perfect result that time!! 😭✨ like the TA looked at it and was like “textbook endpoint” or something like that lol. and we got full points on the lab report too, which was nice 🥹 i think she even wrote “great teamwork” in the comments so that felt really good tbh 🫶
